\begin_body

\begin_layout Title
Inference for agreement coefficients with missing ratings
\end_layout

\begin_layout Abstract
Missing data is a pervasive challenge in studies of interrater agreement,
 yet common agreement coefficients—
such as Conger’s kappa,
 Fleiss’ kappa (and Krippendorff’s alpha),
 and the Brennan–Prediger coefficient—
are often applied without clear justification when ratings are incomplete.
 We develop a general and simple framework for missing data in agreement analysis that supports both categorical and continuous responses,
 allows arbitrary disagreement functions,
 and hold provided the data is missing completely at random.
 Then we propose estimators under the common assumption of rater exchangeability.
 We also study existing estimators of agreement purportedly valid with missing raters:
 The complete-case estimator,
 the subject-wise estimator,
 and the pooled estimator (related to Krippendorff's alpha).
 We study when they remain consistent under missing data,
 derive their correct standard errors,
 and identify settings where the conventional formulas fail when applicable.
 We supply asymptotic covariance matrices that enable joint inference across coefficients,
 and simulations verify the theoretical claims.
 Our proposed estimators are only efficient under a simplifying and unrealistic condition,
 but the loss of efficiency compared to efficient estimator are minor in a simulation study.
 Moreover,
 the methods appear to perform well also under MAR.
 The methods are implemented in an R package 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathtt{misskappa}$
\end_inset

 designed for applied use.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Author
Jonas Moss,
 Rutger van Oest
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Introduction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A chance-corrected agreement coefficient is any coefficient on the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{x}=1-\frac{d}{d_{x}}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

 is a measure of disagreement and 
\begin_inset Formula $d_{x}$
\end_inset

 a measure of chance disagreement.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,y)\geq0$
\end_inset

 be a symmetric loss function satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,x)=0$
\end_inset

.
 The most common are nominal 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,y)=1[x\neq y]$
\end_inset

,
 absolute value (or linear) 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,y)=|x-y|$
\end_inset

,
 and quadratic 
\begin_inset Formula $l(x,y)=(x-y)^{2}$
\end_inset

.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 be a random vector with 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 components.
 Define disagreement as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
d=\binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j<k}E[l(X_{j}^{\star},X_{k}^{\star})].\label{eq:population disagreement}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

We cover three variants of chance disagreement,
 the Fleiss-type,
 Cohen-type,
 and Brennan–Prediger-type.
 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray}
d_{F} & = & R^{-2}\sum_{j,k}E[l(X_{ij}^{\star},X_{i'k}^{\star})],\label{eq:fleiss disagreement}\\
d_{C} & = & \binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j<k}E[l(X_{ij}^{\star},X_{i'k}^{\star})],\label{eq:cohendisagreement}\\
d_{BP} & =\label{eq:bp disagreement}
\end{eqnarray}

\end_inset

Interpretations of these can be found elsewhere,
 e.g.,
 [[]],
 [[]],
 [[]].
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
For complete data the kappa coefficients are estimated using the natural sample counterparts.
 Their standard errors may be found using either multinomial theory [cite] or the theory of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics and 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

-statistics [Moss].
 
\end_layout

