\begin_layout Standard
The theory of missing data can be applied to agreement coefficients provided we assume data is missing at random (MAR).
 When the data is discrete we may use maximum likelihood along with the delta method to estimate the coefficients.
 This method will be explored in a future paper.
 If the data isn't discrete we may use (Tsiatis,
 Robins) to deduce the efficient influence function for the numerator and denominator.
 For multirater Cohen's kappa we obtain,
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
a & \xi & \zeta\\
b
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Observe that both the numerator and denominator requires non-parametric estimates of 
\begin_inset Formula $E[l(..]$
\end_inset

.
 This poses a major pratical hurdle for little gain.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
Formulating the parameter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $X\in(\mathbb{R}\cup\text{NA})^{\mathcal{R}}$
\end_inset

 be the observed data and 
\begin_inset Formula $R\in\{0,1\}^{\mathcal{R}}$
\end_inset

 be defined by 
\begin_inset Formula $R_{j}=1[X_{j}\neq\text{NA}]$
\end_inset

.
 Define the probabilities 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{j}=E(R_{j})$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{jk}=E(R_{j}R_{k})$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the parameter
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
d_{jk} & = & E\left[l(X_{j},X_{k})R_{j}R_{k}\right]\pi_{jk}^{-1},\\
d & = & \binom{\mathcal{R}}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j<k}d_{jk}.
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Suppose there is a latent 
\begin_inset Formula $X^{\star}$
\end_inset

 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}=R_{i}X_{i}^{\star}$
\end_inset

.
 Then
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
d_{jk} & = & E\left[l(X_{j},X_{k})R_{j}R_{k}\right]\pi_{jk}^{-1}\\
 & = & E\left\{ E\left[l(X_{j},X_{k})R_{j}R_{k}\mid X_{i}^{\star},X_{j}^{\star}\right]\right\} \pi_{jk}^{-1}\\
 &  & E\left\{ l(X_{j},X_{k})E(R_{j}R_{k}\mid X_{i}^{\star},X_{j}^{\star})\right\} \pi_{jk}^{-1}
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

Moreover,
 suppose 
\begin_inset Formula $E[R_{j}R_{k}\mid X_{i}^{\star},X_{j}^{\star}]=E[R_{j}R_{k}]=\pi_{jk}$
\end_inset

.
 If follows that
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
E\left\{ l(X_{j},X_{k})E(R_{j}R_{k}\mid X_{i}^{\star},X_{j}^{\star})\right\} \pi_{jk}^{-1} & = & E[l(X_{j}^{\star},X_{k}^{\star})],
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset

which equals the original disagreement 
\begin_inset Formula $d$
\end_inset

.
 Hence our goal is to estimate 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\frac{E[l(X_{j},X_{k})R_{j}R_{k}]}{E[R_{j}R_{k}]}.
\]

\end_inset

Now we must find the efficient influence function for this problem.
 To start,
 assume 
\begin_inset Formula $E[l^{2}(X_{j},X_{k})R_{j}R_{k}]<\infty$
\end_inset

 to ensure asymptotic normality of the 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistic for complete data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Numerator and denominator are both 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics and it's well-known that 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics are non-parametrically efficient.
 Hence we obtain 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{l}_{jk}=n^{-1}\sum_{i=1}^{n}l(X_{ij},X_{ik})R_{ij}R_{ik}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\pi}_{jk}=n^{-1}\sum_{i=1}^{n}R_{ij}R_{ik}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{d}_{jk}=\hat{l}_{jk}/\hat{\pi}_{jk}$
\end_inset

.
 The influence function of 
\begin_inset Formula $(\hat{l}_{jk},\hat{\pi}_{jk})$
\end_inset

 is obtained through standard 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics theory,
 and the influence function of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{d}_{jk}=(\pi_{jk}^{-1},-l_{jk}\pi_{jk}^{-2})(\psi_{l_{jk}},\psi_{\pi_{jk}})^{T}=\psi_{l_{jk}}\pi_{jk}^{-1}-\psi_{\pi_{jk}}l_{jk}\pi_{ij}^{-2}$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{eqnarray*}
\psi_{d_{jk}}(i) & = & \pi_{ij}^{-1}(l(X_{ij},X_{ik})R_{ij}R_{ik}-l_{jk})-\pi_{ij}^{-2}l_{jk}(R_{ij}R_{ik}-\pi_{ij}),\\
 & = & \pi_{ij}^{-1}(l(X_{ij},X_{ik})R_{ij}R_{ik}-d_{jk}).
\end{eqnarray*}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's see if we can add restrictions to 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 a probability measure over 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

.
 What restrictions do we have on 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(X_{j}=\text{NA}\mid X_{-j})=P(X_{j}=\text{NA})
\]

\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(R_{j}R_{k}\mid X_{i}^{\star},X_{j}^{\star})=P(R_{j}R_{k})
\]

\end_inset

this implies that (?)
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(R_{j}R_{k}\mid X_{I}=x)=P(R_{j}R_{k}\mid X_{I}=y)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $I$
\end_inset

 is any index set and 
\begin_inset Formula $x,y$
\end_inset

 do not contain 
\begin_inset Formula $NA$
\end_inset

s?
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's work with this assumption instead,
 which is weaker but sufficient:
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
P(R_{j}R_{k}\mid X_{i}^{\star},X_{j}^{\star})=P(R_{j}R_{k})
\]

\end_inset

Let's try to construct 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}^{\star}$
\end_inset

,
\begin_inset Formula $X_{j}^{\star}$
\end_inset

 from 
\begin_inset Formula $X.$
\end_inset

 For each 
\begin_inset Formula $j$
\end_inset

 we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
X_{j}^{\star}(\omega)=R_{j}(\omega)X_{j}(\omega)+(1-R_{j}(\omega))Z_{j}(\omega),
\]

\end_inset

and we need to find a 
\begin_inset Formula $Z_{j}$
\end_inset

 that satisfies 
\begin_inset Formula $P(R_{i}R_{j}|X_{i}^{\star},X_{j}^{\star})=P(R_{i}R_{j})$
\end_inset

 OR find a condition that guarantees its existence.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
PMCAR is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $P(X_{i}^{\star},X_{j}^{\star})=P(X_{i}^{\star},X_{j}^{\star}\mid R_{i}R_{j}=1)=P(X_{i},X_{j}\mid R_{i}R_{j}=1).$
\end_inset


\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(X_{j}^{\star},X_{k}^{\star})=p(R_{j}(\omega)X_{j}(\omega)+(1-R_{j}(\omega))Z_{j}(\omega),R_{k}(\omega)X_{k}(\omega)+(1-R_{k}(\omega))Z_{k}(\omega))
\]

\end_inset

So
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(X_{j}^{\star},X_{k}^{\star}\mid R_{j}R_{k}=0)=p(Z_{j}(\omega),Z_{k}(\omega)).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It seems we require
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
p(X_{j}\mid R_{j}R_{k}=1)=p(X_{j}\mid R_{j}R_{l}=1).
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Multirater Cohen's kappa
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the inverse probability weighted 
\emph on
sample disagreement
\emph default
 as 
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{d}=\binom{\mathcal{R}}{2}^{-1}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j<k}l(X_{ij},X_{ik})R_{ij}R_{ik}\hat{\pi}_{jk}^{-1}.\label{eq:ipw disagreement}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

Define the inverse probability weighted sample 
\emph on
Cohen chance disagreement
\emph default
 as
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{d}_{C}=\binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{i'=1}^{n}\sum_{j<k}l(X_{ij},X_{i'k})R_{ij}R_{i'k}\hat{\pi}_{j}^{-1}\hat{\pi}_{k}^{-1}.\label{eq:ipw cohen disagreement}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Then our proposed estimator of Conger's kappa is 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{C}=1-\hat{d}/\hat{d}_{C}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
Assume that 
\begin_inset Formula $\pi_{jk}>0$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $j,k.$
\end_inset

 Then we have 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(a) 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{d}$
\end_inset

,
 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{d}_{C}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{C}$
\end_inset

 are consistent for 
\begin_inset Formula $d,d_{C}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\kappa_{C}$
\end_inset

 provided the data is PMCAR.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(b) If 
\begin_inset Formula $El^{2}(X_{ij},X_{ik})<\infty$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j,k$
\end_inset

,
 then all estimators are asymptotically normal.
 Given PMCAR then the estimators are efficient.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Theorem
(c) The missingness mechanism must be PMCAR for 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{C}$
\end_inset

 to be consistent for all models satisfying 
\begin_inset Formula $El^{2}(X_{ij},X_{ik})<\infty$
\end_inset

 for all 
\begin_inset Formula $i,j,k$
\end_inset

.
