\begin_layout Subsection
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics vs 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

-statistics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
"The U-statistic,
 by design,
 only compares ratings from different subjects (i 
\backslash
neq i').
 This is conceptually analogous to a leave-one-out cross-validation procedure for calculating disagreement.
 For each subject i,
 we are comparing its rating to a 'training set' of all other subjects.
 This ensures that every comparison is genuinely out-of-sample,
 which is known to produce less biased estimates of performance in small samples.
 
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
"The U-statistic approach is similar to the Adjusted R².
 It systematically removes the problematic 'self-comparison' terms that cause overfitting.
 Just as Wherry's formula applies a correction factor to R²,
 the U-statistic structure provides an inherent structural correction that yields an exactly unbiased estimate of the true chance disagreement."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
"The U-statistic enforces a strict 'no self-grading' policy.
 It ensures every single comparison is between two genuinely different subjects (i 
\backslash
neq i'),
 giving us a purer and more trustworthy estimate of chance-level performance."
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

While the standard V-statistic formulation for 
\backslash
hat{d}_C is common due to its simplicity,
 it is instructive to consider a U-statistic alternative.
 The key difference is that the V-statistic includes diagonal terms where a subject's data is compared against itself (i=i'),
 whereas the U-statistic strictly compares data between different subjects (i 
\backslash
neq i').
 This distinction is conceptually analogous to the principle of leave-one-out cross-validation (LOOCV).
 By including the diagonal terms,
 the V-statistic is akin to performing a small part of its evaluation 'in-sample,' which introduces a small but systematic bias,
 particularly with limited data.
 The U-statistic,
 by only using 'out-of-sample' pairs (i 
\backslash
neq i'),
 provides an exactly unbiased estimate of the chance disagreement parameter.
 To investigate whether this theoretical advantage translates to better practical performance,
 we conducted a small simulation...
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
The main reason not to use 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics is tradition.
 All classical agreement coefficients are estimated with 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

-statistics,
 and our proposed estimator and asymptotic variance 
