\begin_layout Proposition
The subject-wise and pooled kappas are consistent if either (a) the missingness is exchangeable or (b) the raters are exchangeable.
 It is generally not consistent when either of these are broken.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
Assume MCAR,
 so that 
\begin_inset Formula $X$
\end_inset

 is independent of 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

.
 Then we have
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left[\frac{\sum_{j<k}l(X_{ij},X_{ik})M_{ij}M_{ik}}{\sum_{j<k}M_{ij}M_{ik}}\mid M\right]=\sum_{j<k}El(X_{ij},X_{ik})\frac{M_{ij}M_{ik}}{\sum_{j<k}M_{ij}M_{ik}}.
\]

\end_inset

Here
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
E\left[\frac{M_{ij}M_{ik}}{\sum_{j<k}M_{ij}M_{ik}}\right]=\binom{\mathcal{R}}{2}^{-1}
\]

\end_inset

if the missingness is exchangeable.
 This equality does 
\emph on
not
\emph default
 hold in general.
 And by the law of total expectation,
 
\begin_inset Formula $E\hat{d}^{SW}=\binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j<k}El(X_{ij},X_{ik})$
\end_inset

.
 By the law of large numbers,
 the estimator is of disagreement is consistent.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proof
On the other hand,
 if the raters themselves are exchangeable,
 then 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{j<k}El(X_{ij},X_{ik})\frac{M_{ij}M_{ik}}{\sum_{j<k}M_{ij}M_{ik}}=El(X_{j},X_{k})\frac{\sum_{j<k}M_{ij}M_{ik}}{\sum_{j<k}M_{ij}M_{ik}}=El(X_{j},X_{k}),$
\end_inset

and the estimator is also consistent.
 An essentially identical analysis shows that 
