\begin_layout Subsection
Pooled estimator
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An intuitive competitor to Gwet's estimator could be called the 
\emph on
pooled estimator
\emph default
.
 Let's briefly define and motivate it by looking at the observed disagreement 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j<k}l(X_{j},X_{k})$
\end_inset

.
 This is the average contribution from each observer to the disagreement,
 one might,
 as Gwet does,
 attempt to estimate each 
\begin_inset Formula $\binom{R}{2}^{-1}\sum_{j<k}l(X_{ij},X_{ik})$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{\sum_{j<k}l(X_{ij},X_{ik})M_{ik}}{\sum_{j<k}M_{ij}M_{ik}}$
\end_inset

.
 Consider the standard estimator of disagreement.
 We may write it as follows.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\sum_{i=1}^{n}\frac{\sum_{j<k}l(X_{ij},X_{ik})}{\binom{R}{2}}=\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j<k}l(X_{ij},X_{ik})}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}\binom{R}{2}}.
\]

\end_inset

To take into account missing raters in the denominator we may either go with the left-hand side,
 as in Gwet's estimator,
 or with the right-hand side.
 If we use the right-hand side we obtain the denominator 
\begin_inset Formula $\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j<k}R_{ij}R_{ik}$
\end_inset

,
 and the resulting estimator of disagreement
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{d}^{P}=\frac{\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j<k}l(X_{ij},X_{ik})R_{ij}R_{ik}}{\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j<k}R_{ij}R_{ik}}.
\]

\end_inset

The chance disagreements are similar,
 and defined as
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{d}_{C}^{P}=\frac{\sum_{i,i'}\sum_{j<k}l(X_{ij},X_{i'k})R_{ij}R_{i'k}}{\sum_{i,i'}\sum_{j<k}R_{ij}R_{i'k}},\quad\hat{d}_{F}^{P}=\frac{\sum_{i,i'}\sum_{j,k}l(X_{ij},X_{i'k})R_{ij}R_{i'k}}{\sum_{i,i'}\sum_{j,k}R_{ij}R_{i'k}}.
\]

\end_inset

Compared to the subject-wise estimator the pooled estimator places more weights on subject with many ratings and less weight on subjects with fewer ratings.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The asymptotic distribution of the pooled estimators may be derived,
 tediously,
 by noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{d}^{P}$
\end_inset

 is a ratio of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{d}_{C}^{P}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{d}_{F}^{P}$
\end_inset

 are ratios of 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

-statistics.
 
\end_layout

