\begin_layout Subsection
Krippendorff's alpha
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let's go through Krippendorff's alpha and find its properties.
 Krippendorff's alpha is typically defined only for discrete data and we keep our analysis in that domain.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Denote 
\begin_inset Formula $o_{ck}$
\end_inset

 as the number of times a pair of raters have classified an item into the categories 
\begin_inset Formula $c,k$
\end_inset

,
 i.e.
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
o_{ck}=\sum_{i=1}^{n}\sum_{j\neq k}1[x_{ij}=c]1[x_{ik}=k],
\]

\end_inset

Now define 
\begin_inset Formula $N=\sum_{c,k}o_{ck}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $n_{c}=\sum_{k}o_{ck}$
\end_inset

.
 Then Krippendorff's alpha,
 typically defined solely as an estimator,
 not a population quantity,
 equals [[Krippendorff 2018,
 p.
 235]]
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\alpha}=1-(N-1)\frac{\sum_{c\neq k}o_{ck}l(c,k)}{\sum_{c\neq k}n_{c}n_{k}l(c,k)}.
\]

\end_inset

Through some simple manipulations (appendix p.
 X),
 we find that
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\hat{\alpha}_{l}=1-\frac{\hat{d}^{AC}}{\hat{d}_{F}^{AC}}+\frac{1}{N}\frac{\hat{d}^{AC}}{\hat{d}_{F}^{AC}}=\hat{\kappa}_{F}^{AC}+\frac{1}{N}(1-\hat{\kappa}_{F}^{AC}).
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{x}^{AC}$
\end_inset

 denotes the available-case estimator.
 Since this estimator is equivalent to 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\kappa}_{F}^{AC}$
\end_inset

 in the limit,
 it inherits its inconsistency and inefficiency properties.
 Moreover,
 since the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

correction term
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{1}{N}(1-\hat{\kappa}_{F}^{AC})$
\end_inset

 is unmotivated statistically,
 there is even less reason to recommend Krippendorff's 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 than the available-case estimator of Fleiss' kappa.
 But as the available-case estimator is efficient under complete data,
 Krippendorff's 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is as well,
 and they share asymptotic standard error.
 Thus it is statistically justified,
 though probably hard to motivate,
 to use the standard error of Fleiss' kappa along with Krippendorff's point estimate when dealing with complete data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A particular characteristic of Krippendorff's alpha is how he recommends tabulating data.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Proposition
Suppose that each subject is rated by exactly two raters and the raters are exchangeable.
 Then Krippendorff's alpha is an efficient estimator of 
