\begin_layout Subsection
Influence functions
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}$
\end_inset

 be asymptotically linear,
 that is,
 an estimator can be written on the form
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sqrt{n}(\hat{\theta}-\theta(P))=\frac{1}{\sqrt{n}}\sum_{i=1}^{n}\psi_{P}(X_{i})+o_{p}(1),\label{eq:influence function}
\end{equation}

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $X_{i}$
\end_inset

 are iid from 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta(P)$
\end_inset

 is a functional.
 Then the asymptotic variance of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}$
\end_inset

 is 
\begin_inset Formula $\Var\psi_{P}(X)$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\psi_{P}$
\end_inset

 is called 
\emph on
the influence function 
\emph default
of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\theta}$
\end_inset


\emph on
.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The name efficient influence function comes from the literature on semiparametric efficiency,
 and can be thought of as the unique influence function of the efficient estimator of a functional 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta(P)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Influence functions for 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The influence function for a 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistic equals its projection
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
for details,
 see one of many introductions to 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Modulo regularity conditions,
 whenever a functional can be phrased on the form 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta(P)=E_{P^{k}}h(X_{1},X_{2},\ldots,X_{k})$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $P^{k}$
\end_inset

 denotes 
\begin_inset Formula $k$
\end_inset

 independent copies of 
\begin_inset Formula $P$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $h$
\end_inset

 is a function,
 then the corresponding 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistic is efficient for 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta(P)$
\end_inset

 in the class 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $E_{P^{k}}h(X_{1},X_{2},\ldots,X_{k})$
\end_inset

 is defined and finite.
 See [[]]] and [[]] for details.
 The 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistic is also UMVUE,
 the uniformly minimum variance unbiased estimator over the class 
\begin_inset Formula $\mathcal{P}$
\end_inset

,
 but this isn't too interesting to us since we deal with ratios of 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistics.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The influence function of a 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

-statistic is identical to the influence function of a 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

-statistic.
 However,
 we may choose the estimate the influence function using either the 
\begin_inset Formula $U$
\end_inset

- or 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

-statistic formulations.
 These are asymptotically equivalent,
 but the difference matters in small samples.
\end_layout

